  "prompt": "What is the shape of market demand curve? It is not linear.. Bt then also we call it a linear why?",
  "response": "The market demand curve is typically depicted as a downward-sloping curve, not strictly linear. Let me clarify the concept:\n\n1. Actual Demand Curve (Non-Linear):\n- Real-world demand curves are usually curved/non-linear\n- Reflects complex consumer behavior\n- Varies based on different price points\n\n2. Linear Representation:\n- Simplified mathematical model\n- Used for easier economic analysis\n- Approximates the general trend of demand\n- Helps in understanding basic economic principles\n\n3. Why We Often Use Linear Representation:\n- Easier mathematical calculations\n- Provides basic understanding of demand-price relationship\n- Serves as a starting point for more complex economic models\n- Helps in quick graphical representations\n\n4. Factors Affecting Non-Linearity:\n- Consumer preferences\n- Income levels\n- Substitutes availability\n- Marginal utility variations\n\n5. Practical Approach:\n- Linear representation is an approximation\n- Useful for basic economic reasoning\n- More complex models used for detailed analysis\n\nKey Point: While we often draw a linear demand curve, it's understood that real-world demand is more nuanced and complex.\n\nThe linear representation is a simplification that helps in understanding fundamental economic principles.",
